    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that these reforms will hurt growth is a classic case of the \"trickle-down\" fallacy, which assumes that punishing the wealthy will magically incentivize investment rather than simply stifling it. Critics often fear that higher taxes on high earners will cause capital flight or reduce innovation, but this ignores the reality that the current system already discourages investment through massive loopholes and tax avoidance. The real danger isn't the proposed reforms; it's the status quo, which allows the ultra-wealthy to extract wealth without contributing to the economy. Focusing on these distortions is a distraction from the urgent need to build a fairer, more resilient economy.",
